.TH NUKE 1 "2026-04-23" "nuke" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
nuke \- safely move directory contents to a timestamped trash folder
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B nuke
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B nuke
clears a target directory by moving its contents to
.IR ~/.nuke-trash/<timestamp>/
instead of permanently deleting them.
Nothing is ever erased — every item can be recovered by browsing the trash folder.
.PP
By default
.B nuke
targets the current working directory and moves only regular files,
leaving subdirectories in place.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-all
Move files \fIand\fR subdirectories (everything at the top level of the target).
.TP
.BR \-\-files\-only
Move only regular files; leave subdirectories untouched.
This is the default behavior and is rarely needed explicitly.
.TP
.BR \-t ", " \-\-target " \fIPATH\fR"
Target directory to nuke.
Defaults to the current working directory when omitted.
.TP
.BR \-\-force
Skip the interactive confirmation prompt and proceed immediately.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print a short usage summary and exit.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Print the version number and exit.
.SH TRASH BEHAVIOR
Each invocation creates a unique timestamped directory:
.PP
.RS
.I ~/.nuke-trash/YYYY-MM-DD_HH-MM-SS/
.RE
.PP
Items moved during that run are placed inside it.
Because each run gets its own folder there are no collisions between separate invocations.
.PP
To recover items, move them back manually:
.PP
.RS
.EX
mv ~/.nuke-trash/2026-04-23_10-00-00/myfile.txt ./
.EE
.RE
.PP
To permanently discard all trash:
.PP
.RS
.EX
rm -rf ~/.nuke-trash
.EE
.RE
.SH SAFETIES
.B nuke
refuses to operate on
.I $HOME
or
.IR / .
It will exit with an error rather than move the contents of either directory.
.SH EXAMPLES
Preview and confirm before nuking files in the current directory:
.PP
.RS
.EX
nuke
.EE
.RE
.PP
Nuke only files in \fI/tmp/scratch\fR without prompting:
.PP
.RS
.EX
nuke \-t /tmp/scratch \-\-force
.EE
.RE
.PP
Nuke everything (files + subdirectories) in \fI/tmp/scratch\fR:
.PP
.RS
.EX
nuke \-\-all \-t /tmp/scratch \-\-force
.EE
.RE
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.nuke-trash/
Root trash directory.
Each run appends a timestamped subdirectory.
.SH AUTHOR
Written by Andres Fritsche Ogando.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR rm (1),
.BR mv (1)
